ce:section.ce:para:
CQDs are synthesized by green hydrothermal way using citric acid as a precursor in DMF solvent. TEM image shows the shape and size of the prepared CQDs. From TEM measurement it is observed that spherical shapes CQDs are formed. Diameter of the CQDs varies from 3 to 5 nm [Fig. 1
                        ]. The size distribution histogram of CQDs was provided in Fig. 2
                        . From the histogram, we can see that maximum no of the particles have size between 3 and 5 nm.

The absorption spectrum of as prepared CQDs. is shown in Fig. 3
                        . In most of the literature, it is reported that CQDs synthesized shows excitation wavelength-dependents emission property. When excitation wavelength is shifted from blue to red region, the emission maxima is also shifted from blue to red [as shown in Fig. 4
                        ]. This phenomenon is occurred due to micro heterogeneity or size distribution factor of the system[78].

In order to study the interaction between surfactants and CQD we measured the change in fluorescence property of CQD in presence of various surfactants like CTAB, SDS, TX-100, CPC and Brij-35 [Fig. 5
                        ]. These surfactants were added to CQD solution maintaining the pH of the solution 7 where the emission of the CQDs is maximum [Fig. S1]. It is observed that CPC surfactant can remarkably quench emission intensity of CQDs. As the surfactant concentration was increased step by step the fluorescence intensity also decreased steadily and it followed a linear relation up to surfactant concentration of 40 mM. At very low CPC concentration I/I0 decreased steeply. Above a certain value of CPC the decrease was not so prominent. It is obvious from the graph that the data belongs to two different sets. It was possible to fit both the data set linearly. The point where the two fitted lines intersect corresponds to the CMC of the surfactant (Fig. 6
                        ). In this process the CMC of CPC was found to be 1.5 mM and this value is close to the previously reported CMC value obtained by other methods [80].

We investigate the fluorescence property of the synthesized CQDs in presence of different surfactants like cationic (CPC, CTAB), anionic (SDS), and neutral (TX100, BRIJ-35.) from pre-micelle concentration to post-micelle concentration for each of the surfactant in aqua medium. The concentration of the CQDs is kept constant throughout the whole study and it is 0.5 mg.mL
                        −1. Undergoing this study, it is observed that only CPC can quench the fluorescence of the CQDs and is maximum after post micelle concentration without any creating surface of separation whereas the other surfactant cannot able to quench the fluorescence property of the CQDs. This quenching of fluorescence intensity of the CQDs is used to determine the CMC of that surfactant and it comes out to relevant with the literature value. By taking the quenched solution of the CQDs-CPC, we performed the HR-TEM which exhibit the formation of spherical vesicles with an average size of 70 nm whereas in case of other surfactant there is no evidence of formation of vesicles [Fig. 7
                        ].

It was clear from the steady-state UV–VIS investigation that neither a ground-state complex nor any interaction between CPC and CQDs occurred. Using TCSPC, we have investigated the fluorescent CQDs' lifetimes both with and without CPC surfactant. According to the TCSPC study, the lifespan of the CPC reduces when the surfactant CPC is present. Therefore, we propose that quenching is dynamic in nature. The quenching of fluorescence property is due to oxidative photo induced electron transfer process that takes place due to transfer of electrons from excited CQDs to the LUMO of the quencher. Here our synthesized CQDs are an electron rich centre as supported by the high negative zeta potential value (-14.2 ± 0.2 mV) of the CQDs [Fig. 8]. In this work, the CQDs behave as an electron donor the CPC surfactant as electron receptor. The energy of the HOMO and LUMO of all participating surfactants are calculated by using density functional theory (DFT) as implemented in Gaussian 16 [85] with B3LYP/6-31G** level of theory [Table 2
                        ]. From the energy gap it is evident that the CPC surfactant has minimum HOMO & LUMO gap, which is equal to 2.62 eV and it is lower than the energy band gap of the CQDs which is 3.65 eV. Most importantly, the LUMO levels of these types of CQDs lie in the range of 3.5–4.5 eV [86,87] which brings necessary energy level alignment (LUMO of the donor is at energetically higher position than that of the acceptor) for photo-induced electron transfer (PET) from CQD to CPC. From all the experimental finding it is evident that firstly the life time of the CQDs decreases with addition of the quencher [Figure S2] and secondly the energy difference between the LUMOs of CQDs and CPC surfactant (thermodynamic driving force ΔG = LUMOdonor– LUMOacceptor) helps the electronic transition from the excited state of the CQDs to the LUMO of CPC which is oxidative photo-induced electron transfer (PET) process [Scheme 2
                        ]. This is the main driving force over electrostatic force of attraction that leads to vesicle formation with CPC surfactant over others without any phase separation.
